				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Hedge Fund Managers Headed for Divorce</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Sydney Ember			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-25T11:32:17+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 25, 2014 7:32 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 25, 2014 7:32 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/morning-agenda-hedge-fund-managers-headed-for-divorce/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Hedge Fund Managers Headed for Divorce" data-description="Kenneth C. Griffin, the head of Citadel, has filed for divorce from his wife, Anne Dias Griffin. | President Obama on Thursday called for an end to so-called inversions. | How AbbVie wooed Shire. | A secret in the bank bailout of Cyprus stirs resentment.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> HEDGE FUND MANAGERS HEADED FOR DIVORCE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> For a decade, Kenneth C. Griffin and his wife, Anne Dias Griffin, were a financial powerhouse, two hedge fund managers who captivated the Chicago social scene, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/kenneth-griffin-files-for-divorce-from-anne-dias-griffin">Michael J. de la Merced and Alexandra Stevenson write in DealBook</a></b>. But on Wednesday, Mr. Griffin, the head of the $20 billion investment firm Citadel, filed a divorce petition in Cook County, Ill., citing âirreconcilable differencesâ after 11 years of marriage. Ms. Dias Griffin has fired back publicly, claiming to have been blindsided by the move. Now, the domestic dispute <b>threatens to push the private couple into the spotlight</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Griffin and Ms. Dias Griffin have a rarefied status in the financial worldâs firmament, defined by both their individual and collective successes, Mr. de la Merced and Ms. Stevenson write. From the beginning, <b>the Griffins epitomized ambition</b>. Mr. Griffin built Citadel into a multibillion-dollar hedge fund and brokerage firm, amassing a personal fortune estimated at $5.5 billion. For her part, Ms. Dias Griffin quickly ascended the ranks of Wall Street before founding her own investment firm, Aragon Global Management. </p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">OBAMA URGES END TO INVERSION DEALS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> President Obama on Thursday called for Congress to strip away tax advantages that have encouraged a rush of mergers and acquisitions that give companies an overseas base while they maintain their presence in the United States, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/us/obama-to-urge-end-to-loophole-letting-firms-shield-profits-abroad-.html">Michael D. Shear and David Gelles write in DealBook</a></b>. In an appearance at a technical college that was intended to focus on job training, the president used harsh language to describe United States companies that acquire overseas companies to relocate for tax reasons, known as inversions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The presidentâs rebuke came as a wave of United States companies has sought such inversions, which has resulted in a <b>growing consensus on Capitol Hill that the rush should be stopped</b>. Lawmakers from both parties worry that the more companies move their headquarters abroad, the more the American tax base is being compromised. Democrats and Republicans seem to agree that a short-term fix is needed, but there is partisan disagreement about what anti-inversion legislation should look like. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, <b>the president called on members of Congress to take action</b> on inversions even if they disagreed with his broader calls for changes to the tax system that would lower corporate rates. The decision to focus on the tax loophole is part of a strategy to position the president on the side of what White House officials call a new economic patriotism. He is pressing that argument as the fall midterm elections approach.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ABBVIEâS WOOING OF SHIRE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> How the pharmaceutical giant AbbVie came to win its European rival Shire demonstrates that even in the middle of a new boom in mergers and acquisitions, a hefty premium is no guarantee of success, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/to-woo-shire-abbvie-trod-cautiously-in-takeover-bid">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a></b>. âHad AbbVie pushed too hard, had Shire been entrenched or had investors been too passive, the deal might never have happened,â he writes. In sealing the deal last week, AbbVie âperformed a high-wire act, balancing cross-border regulations, a short time frame and international shareholders.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the spring, <b>Shireâs board rebuffed AbbVieâs initial offer</b> of about $40 billion. Around that same time, AstraZeneca, the giant British drug maker, had watched a $119 billion offer from Pfizer evaporate in the face of missteps and bluster from both sides. But Shireâs rejection was not enough to deter AbbVie, according to an account based on interviews with people with knowledge of the negotiations. Still, Susan Kilsby, the chairwoman of Shire, agreed to meet with AbbVie, in Paris, only after AbbVie had submitted its third bid. After being rejected again, Richard Gonzalez, AbbVieâs chief executive, intimated he <b>would not shy away from a public fight</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After news of its interest in Shire leaked, <b>AbbVie found lessons in Pfizerâs missteps</b>. For one, Mr. Gonzalez and his advisers at JPMorgan decided that instead of simply stating the most recent bid, AbbVie would announce the series of bids to demonstrate that the company had already increased its offer substantially. AbbVie also decided not to disparage Shireâs performance. Shire, for its part, responded differently than AstraZeneca did. In the end, the negotiations <b>resulted in the biggest deal of the year</b>, at $54 billion.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Data on <b>durable goods orders</b> is out at 8:30 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">A SECRET IN CYPRUS STIRS RESENTMENT <span class="divider"> | </span></span> âOf all the financial implosions in the eurozone, few matched last yearâs collapse of tiny Cyprus in terms of drama and chaos,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/a-secret-in-cyprus-stirs-resentment/">Landon Thomas Jr. writes in DealBook</a></b>. Now, the foundation of the islandâs multibillion-euro bailout, an analysis by the bond giant Pimco, is being challenged by economists, lawyers and politicians in Cyprus, who argue that the analysis relied too heavily on aggressive financial assumptions that in some cases  inflated how much cash banks needed to survive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The basis for the criticism comes from a separate BlackRock study</b> commissioned by the Cypriot central bank shortly before Pimco issued its report. Voicing concerns over Pimcoâs models and its approach, the central bank chief asked BlackRock to dissect the work of its rival. The BlackRock study, which has never been publicly released, suggests that the banksâ needs were â¬1 billion less than Pimcoâs estimate of â¬8.8 billion; <b>central bank officials did not brief the new Cypriot government</b> on the reportâs existence at the time of bailout negotiations in March 2013. Government investigators say capital requirements were even lower, just over â¬6 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOver the last year, the island has been swept up by Watergate-style hearings with many of the principal actors in the economyâs collapse and subsequent rescue,â Mr. Thomas writes. âBeyond the calumny and conspiracy theories, one question has persisted: Did Pimco succumb to pressure from the central bank and the three bodies lending money to Cyprus â the International Monetary Fund, the European Central Bank and European Commission â <b>to punish the banks by inflating their cash needs</b>?â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
</div>
